# Git Workflow

## Session Start

Run these commands at the start of each session:

```bash
git status
git branch --show-current
git log --oneline -3
```

If >10 files have uncommitted changes, alert the user before starting new work.

**Multi-repo awareness:** If your workspace contains multiple git repos, always verify which repo you're in before running git commands.

## Commit Principles

- Commit after each logical unit of work (one feature, one fix, one refactor)
- Write commit messages that explain WHY, not just WHAT
- Never leave a session with large uncommitted changes
- When a change touches 5+ files, commit in logical groups and build-verify between commits

## Branch Rules

- `main` for production-ready code
- Feature branches (`feature/description`) for experimental work
- Never force-push to `main`
- Ignore auto-created `cursor/*` branches

## Before Committing

- If the commit adds imports to new files, those files MUST be included in the same commit
- Verify the build would succeed from scratch: all imported files must be tracked
- Untracked files that are imported by tracked files = broken commit

## Before Deploying

- All changes committed, `git diff` shows nothing
- Build succeeds locally

## Structural Changes (Red Flags)

Structural changes: renaming tabs, restructuring navigation, changing data models, reorganizing files, changing routing.

- COMMIT current working state before starting structural changes
- If you've touched >5 files without committing, stop and commit
- If `git diff --stat` shows >500 lines changed, stop and commit
- Build-verify after each phase of a structural change
- Never combine "create new files + wire into app + remove old files" in a single uncommitted batch

## Project-Specific Customization

Add project-specific git rules here:
- Document structure patterns (e.g., check `SESSION_LOG.md` at session start)
- Build verification steps
- Deployment workflows
- Any mobile-specific considerations
